For each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \in  G]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{\sigma }(x)]]></fr:tex> be the polynomial obtained by applying <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> to the coefficients of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[g^{\sigma }(x)=\prod _{\beta \in  G\alpha }(x-\sigma \beta ).]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\alpha )=0]]></fr:tex> and irreducibility implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is the minimal polynomial of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> (i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=m_{\alpha }(x)]]></fr:tex>), which implies
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} g(x).]]></fr:tex>
We see
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(\sigma \alpha )=f^{\sigma }(\alpha )=f(\alpha )=0,]]></fr:tex>
which implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G\alpha ]]></fr:tex> are roots of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. This then implies
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[g(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} f(x).]]></fr:tex>
Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g=f]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
